<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="166" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="166">Comments</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="166">
Sub-adult male specimen was collected from mid-elevation slopes while calling from low vegetation. This species is part of the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pfeffer" baseAuthorityYear="1893" class="Amphibia" family="Arthroleptidae" genus="Leptopelis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Leptopelis argenteus" order="Anura" pageId="3" pageNumber="166" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="argenteus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="166">Leptopelis argenteus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. Some authors regard this as a valid species (
<bibRefCitation author="Poynton, JC" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Natal Museum" pageId="10" pageNumber="173" pagination="161 - 229" refId="B59" refString="Poynton, JC, Broadley, DG, 1987. Amphibia Zambeziaca 3. Rhacophoridae and Hyperoliidae. Annals of the Natal Museum 28: 161 - 229" title="Amphibia Zambeziaca 3. Rhacophoridae and Hyperoliidae." volume="28" year="1987">Poynton and Broadley 1987</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Schiotz, A" journalOrPublisher="Edition Chimaira, Frankfurt am Main" pageId="10" pageNumber="173" refId="B62" refString="Schiotz, A, 1999. Treefrogs of Africa. Edition Chimaira, Frankfurt am Main" title="Treefrogs of Africa." year="1999">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Schiøtz">Schiotz</normalizedToken>
1999
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Channing, A" journalOrPublisher="Cornell University Press, New York" pageId="10" pageNumber="173" refId="B29" refString="Channing, A, Howell, KM, 2006. Amphibians of East Africa. Cornell University Press, New York" title="Amphibians of East Africa." year="2006">Channing and Howell 2006</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Pickersgill, M" journalOrPublisher="Frog search. Results of expeditions to Southern and Eastern Africa from 1993 - 1999" pageId="10" pageNumber="173" refId="B52" refString="Pickersgill, M, 2007. . Frog search. Results of expeditions to Southern and Eastern Africa from 1993-1999 Volume 28" volume="Volume 28" year="2007">Pickersgill 2007</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Du Preez, LH" journalOrPublisher="Struik Nature, Cape Town" pageId="10" pageNumber="173" publicationUrl="10.1111/j.1096-3642.2011.00773.x" refId="B37" refString="Du Preez, LH, Carruthers, VC, 2009. A Complete Guide to the Frogs of Southern Africa. Struik Nature, Cape Town, DOI: 10.1111/j.1096-3642.2011.00773.x" title="A Complete Guide to the Frogs of Southern Africa" url="10.1111/j.1096-3642.2011.00773.x" year="2009">Du Preez and Carruthers 2009</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Mercurio, V" journalOrPublisher="Edition Chimaira, Frankfurt / M" pageId="10" pageNumber="173" refId="B47" refString="Mercurio, V, 2011. Amphibians of Malawi, an analysis of their richness and community diversity in a changing landscape. Edition Chimaira, Frankfurt/M" title="Amphibians of Malawi, an analysis of their richness and community diversity in a changing landscape" year="2011">Mercurio 2011</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Ohler, A" journalOrPublisher="Journal of East African Natural History" pageId="10" pageNumber="173" pagination="73 - 124" publicationUrl="10.2982/028.103.0203" refId="B50" refString="Ohler, A, Fretey, T, 2014. Going back to Rovuma: the frog fauna of a coastal dry forest, and a checklist of the amphibians of Mozambique. Journal of East African Natural History 103: 73 - 124, DOI: 10.2982/028.103.0203" title="Going back to Rovuma: the frog fauna of a coastal dry forest, and a checklist of the amphibians of Mozambique." url="10.2982/028.103.0203" volume="103" year="2014">
Ohler and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Frétey">Fretey</normalizedToken>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
), while 
<bibRefCitation author="Frost, DR" journalOrPublisher="American Museum of Natural History, New York" pageId="10" pageNumber="173" publicationUrl="http://research.amnh.org/herpetology/amphibia/index.html" refId="B40" refString="Frost, DR, 2016. Amphibian Species of the World: an Online Reference, Version 6.0. American Museum of Natural History, New York, http://research.amnh.org/herpetology/amphibia/index.html [accessed 1 April 2016]" title="Amphibian Species of the World: an Online Reference, Version 6.0" url="http://research.amnh.org/herpetology/amphibia/index.html" year="2016">Frost (2016)</bibRefCitation>
considers it as a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pfeffer" baseAuthorityYear="1893" class="Amphibia" family="Arthroleptidae" genus="Leptopelis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Leptopelis argenteus" order="Anura" pageId="3" pageNumber="166" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="argenteus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="166">Leptopelis argenteus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on similar calls. Herein we consider 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Poynton" authorityYear="1985" class="Amphibia" family="Arthroleptidae" genus="Leptopelis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Leptopelis broadleyi" order="Anura" pageId="3" pageNumber="166" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="broadleyi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="166">Leptopelis broadleyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a valid species pending further investigation.
</paragraph>
